# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: docker-containers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Multi-stage builds let you reduce the size of your final image, by creating a cleaner separation between the building of your image and the final output.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Split your Dockerfile instructions into distinct stages to make sure that the resulting output only contains the files that are needed to run the application.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Using multiple stages can also let you build more efficiently by executing build steps in parallel.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] See Multi-stage builds for more information.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] If you have multiple images with a lot in common, consider creating a reusable stage that includes the shared components, and basing your unique stages on that.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Docker only needs to build the common stage once.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This means that your derivative images use memory on the Docker host more efficiently and load more quickly.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] It's also easier to maintain a common base stage ("Don't repeat yourself"), than it is to have multiple different stages doing similar things.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The first step towards achieving a secure image is to choose the right base image.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] When choosing an image, ensure it's built from a trusted source and keep it small.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] When you pick your base image, look out for the badges indicating that the image is part of these programs.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] When building your own image from a Dockerfile, ensure you choose a minimal base image that matches your requirements.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] A smaller base image not only offers portability and fast downloads, but also shrinks the size of your image and minimizes the number of vulnerabilities introduced through the dependencies.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] You should also consider using two types of base image: one for building and unit testing, and another (typically slimmer) image for production.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] In the later stages of development, your image may not require build tools such as compilers, build systems, and debugging tools.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] A small image with minimal dependencies can considerably lower the attack surface.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Building an image is taking a snapshot of that image at that moment.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] That includes any base images, libraries, or other software you use in your build.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] To keep your images up-to-date and secure, rebuild your images regularly with updated dependencies.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The following Dockerfile uses the `24.04` tag of the `ubuntu` image.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Over time, that tag may resolve to a different underlying version of the `ubuntu` image, as the publisher rebuilds the image with new security patches and updated libraries.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The `--pull` flag forces Docker to check for and download a newer version of the base image, even if you have a version cached locally.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This gets the latest available versions of dependencies from package managers like `apt-get` or `npm`.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] It does not pull a fresh base image — for that, use `--pull`.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The two flags serve distinct purposes and can be combined.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Also consider pinning base image versions.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] To exclude files not relevant to the build, without restructuring your source repository, use a `.dockerignore` file.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This file supports exclusion patterns similar to `.gitignore` files.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For information on creating one, see Dockerignore file.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The image defined by your Dockerfile should generate containers that are as ephemeral as possible.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Ephemeral means that the container can be stopped and destroyed, then rebuilt and replaced with an absolute minimum set up and configuration.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Refer to Processes under *The Twelve-factor App* methodology to get a feel for the motivations of running containers in such a stateless fashion.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Avoid installing extra or unnecessary packages just because they might be nice to have.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For example, you don’t need to include a text editor in a database image.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] When you avoid installing extra or unnecessary packages, your images have reduced complexity, reduced dependencies, reduced file sizes, and reduced build times.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Each container should have only one concern.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Decoupling applications into multiple containers makes it easier to scale horizontally and reuse containers.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For instance, a web application stack might consist of three separate containers, each with its own unique image, to manage the web application, database, and an in-memory cache in a decoupled manner.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Limiting each container to one process is a good rule of thumb, but it's not a hard and fast rule.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For example, not only can containers be spawned with an init process, some programs might spawn additional processes of their own accord.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For instance, Celery can spawn multiple worker processes, and Apache can create one process per request.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Use your best judgment to keep containers as clean and modular as possible.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] If containers depend on each other, you can use Docker container networks to ensure that these containers can communicate.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Whenever possible, sort multi-line arguments alphanumerically to make maintenance easier.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This helps to avoid duplication of packages and make the list much easier to update.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This also makes PRs a lot easier to read and review.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Adding a space before a backslash (`\`) helps as well.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] When building an image, Docker steps through the instructions in your Dockerfile, executing each in the order specified.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For each instruction, Docker checks whether it can reuse the instruction from the build cache.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Understanding how the build cache works, and how cache invalidation occurs, is critical for ensuring faster builds.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For more information about the Docker build cache and how to optimize your builds, see Docker build cache.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Image tags are mutable, meaning a publisher can update a tag to point to a new image.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This is useful because it lets publishers update tags to point to newer versions of an image.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] And as an image consumer, it means you automatically get the new version when you re-build your image.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For example, if you specify `FROM alpine:3.21` in your Dockerfile, `3.21` resolves to the latest patch version for `3.21`.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] At one point in time, the `3.21` tag might point to version 3.21.1 of the image.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] If you rebuild the image 3 months later, the same tag might point to a different version, such as 3.21.4.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This publishing workflow is best practice, and most publishers use this tagging strategy, but it isn't enforced.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The downside with this is that you're not guaranteed to get the same for every build.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This could result in breaking changes, and it means you also don't have an audit trail of the exact image versions that you're using.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] To fully secure your supply chain integrity, you can pin the image version to a specific digest.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] By pinning your images to a digest, you're guaranteed to always use the same image version, even if a publisher replaces the tag with a new image.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For example, the following Dockerfile pins the Alpine image to the same tag as earlier, `3.21`, but this time with a digest reference as well.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] With this Dockerfile, even if the publisher updates the `3.21` tag, your builds would still use the pinned image version: `a8560b36e8b8210634f77d9f7f9efd7ffa463e380b75e2e74aff4511df3ef88c`.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] While this helps you avoid unexpected changes, it's also more tedious to have to look up and include the image digest for base image versions manually each time you want to update it.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] And you're opting out of automated security fixes, which is likely something you want to get.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Docker Scout's default **Up-to-Date Base Images** policy checks whether the base image version you're using is in fact the latest version.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This policy also checks if pinned digests in your Dockerfile correspond to the correct version.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] If a publisher updates an image that you've pinned, the policy evaluation returns a non-compliant status, indicating that you should update your image.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Docker Scout also supports an automated remediation workflow for keeping your base images up-to-date.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] When a new image digest is available, Docker Scout can automatically raise a pull request on your repository to update your Dockerfiles to use the latest version.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This is better than using a tag that changes the version automatically, because you're in control and you have an audit trail of when and how the change occurred.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For more information about automatically updating your base images with Docker Scout, see Remediation.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] When you check in a change to source control or create a pull request, use GitHub Actions or another CI/CD pipeline to automatically build and tag a Docker image and test it.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Follow these recommendations on how to properly use the Dockerfile instructions to create an efficient and maintainable Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Whenever possible, use current official images as the basis for your images.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Docker recommends the Alpine image as it is tightly controlled and small in size (under 6 MB), while still being a full Linux distribution.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For more information about the `FROM` instruction, see Dockerfile reference for the FROM instruction.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] You can add labels to your image to help organize images by project, record licensing information, to aid in automation, or for other reasons.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For each label, add a line beginning with `LABEL` with one or more key-value pairs.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The following examples show the different acceptable formats.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Explanatory comments are included inline.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Strings with spaces must be quoted or the spaces must be escaped.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Inner quote characters (`"`), must also be escaped.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Prior to Docker 1.10, it was recommended to combine all labels into a single `LABEL` instruction, to prevent extra layers from being created.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This is no longer necessary, but combining labels is still supported.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] See Understanding object labels for guidelines about acceptable label keys and values.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For information about querying labels, refer to the items related to filtering in Managing labels on objects.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] See also LABEL in the Dockerfile reference.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Split long or complex `RUN` statements on multiple lines separated with backslashes to make your Dockerfile more readable, understandable, and maintainable.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For example, you can chain commands with the `&&` operator, and use escape characters to break long commands into multiple lines.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] By default, backslash escapes a newline character, but you can change it with the `escape` directive.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For more information about `RUN`, see Dockerfile reference for the RUN instruction.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] One common use case for `RUN` instructions in Debian-based images is to install software using `apt-get`.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Because `apt-get` installs packages, the `RUN apt-get` command has several counter-intuitive behaviors to look out for.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Always combine `RUN apt-get update` with `apt-get install` in the same `RUN` statement.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Using `apt-get update` alone in a `RUN` statement causes caching issues and subsequent `apt-get install` instructions to fail.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] After building the image, all layers are in the Docker cache.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Docker sees the initial and modified instructions as identical and reuses the cache from previous steps.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] As a result the `apt-get update` isn't executed because the build uses the cached version.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Because the `apt-get update` isn't run, your build can potentially get an outdated version of the `curl` and `nginx` packages.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Using `RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends` ensures your Dockerfile installs the latest package versions with no further coding or manual intervention.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This technique is known as cache busting.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] You can also achieve cache busting by specifying a package version.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Version pinning forces the build to retrieve a particular version regardless of what’s in the cache.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This technique can also reduce failures due to unanticipated changes in required packages.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Below is a well-formed `RUN` instruction that demonstrates all the `apt-get` recommendations.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The `s3cmd` argument specifies a version `1.1.*`.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] If the image previously used an older version, specifying the new one causes a cache bust of `apt-get update` and ensures the installation of the new version.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Listing packages on each line can also prevent mistakes in package duplication.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] In addition, when you clean up the apt cache by removing `/var/lib/apt/lists` it reduces the image size, since the apt cache isn't stored in a layer.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Since the `RUN` statement starts with `apt-get update`, the package cache is always refreshed prior to `apt-get install`.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Official Debian and Ubuntu images automatically run `apt-get clean`, so explicit invocation is not required.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Docker executes these commands using the `/bin/sh -c` interpreter, which only evaluates the exit code of the last operation in the pipe to determine success.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] In the example above, this build step succeeds and produces a new image so long as the `wc -l` command succeeds, even if the `wget` command fails.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] If you want the command to fail due to an error at any stage in the pipe, prepend `set -o pipefail &&` to ensure that an unexpected error prevents the build from inadvertently succeeding.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The `CMD` instruction should be used to run the software contained in your image, along with any arguments.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] `CMD` should almost always be used in the form of `CMD ["executable", "param1", "param2"]`.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Thus, if the image is for a service, such as Apache and Rails, you would run something like `CMD ["apache2","-DFOREGROUND"]`.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Indeed, this form of the instruction is recommended for any service-based image.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] In most other cases, `CMD` should be given an interactive shell, such as bash, Python and perl.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Using this form means that when you execute something like `docker run -it python`, you’ll get dropped into a usable shell, ready to go.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] `CMD` should rarely be used in the manner of `CMD ["param", "param"]` in conjunction with `ENTRYPOINT`, unless you and your expected users are already quite familiar with how `ENTRYPOINT` works.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For more information about `CMD`, see Dockerfile reference for the CMD instruction.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The `EXPOSE` instruction indicates the ports on which a container listens for connections.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Consequently, you should use the common, traditional port for your application.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For example, an image containing the Apache web server would use `EXPOSE 80`, while an image containing MongoDB would use `EXPOSE 27017` and so on.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For external access, your users can execute `docker run` with a flag indicating how to map the specified port to the port of their choice.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For container linking, Docker provides environment variables for the path from the recipient container back to the source (for example, `MYSQL_PORT_3306_TCP`).
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For more information about `EXPOSE`, see Dockerfile reference for the EXPOSE instruction.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] To make new software easier to run, you can use `ENV` to update the `PATH` environment variable for the software your container installs.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For example, `ENV PATH=/usr/local/nginx/bin:$PATH` ensures that `CMD ["nginx"]` just works.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The `ENV` instruction is also useful for providing the required environment variables specific to services you want to containerize, such as Postgres’s `PGDATA`.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Similar to having constant variables in a program, as opposed to hard-coding values, this approach lets you change a single `ENV` instruction to automatically bump the version of the software in your container.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Each `ENV` line creates a new intermediate layer, just like `RUN` commands.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This means that even if you unset the environment variable in a future layer, it still persists in this layer and its value can be dumped.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] You can test this by creating a Dockerfile like the following, and then building it.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] To prevent this and unset the environment variable, use a `RUN` command with shell commands, to set, use, and unset the variable all in a single layer.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] You can separate your commands with `;` or `&&`.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] If you use the second method, and one of the commands fails, the `docker build` also fails.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Using `\` as a line continuation character for Linux Dockerfiles improves readability.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] You could also put all of the commands into a shell script and have the `RUN` command just run that shell script.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For more information about `ENV`, see Dockerfile reference for the ENV instruction.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] `ADD` and `COPY` are functionally similar.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] `COPY` supports basic copying of files into the container, from the build context or from a stage in a multi-stage build.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] `ADD` supports features for fetching files from remote HTTPS and Git URLs, and extracting tar files automatically when adding files from the build context.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] You'll mostly want to use `COPY` for copying files from one stage to another in a multi-stage build.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] If you need to add files from the build context to the container temporarily to execute a `RUN` instruction, you can often substitute the `COPY` instruction with a bind mount instead.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Bind mounts are more efficient than `COPY` for including files from the build context in the container.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Note that bind-mounted files are only added temporarily for a single `RUN` instruction, and don't persist in the final image.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] If you need to include files from the build context in the final image, use `COPY`.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The `ADD` instruction is best for when you need to download a remote artifact as part of your build.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] `ADD` is better than manually adding files using something like `wget` and `tar`, because it ensures a more precise build cache.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] `ADD` also has built-in support for checksum validation of the remote resources, and a protocol for parsing branches, tags, and subdirectories from Git URLs.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The following example uses `ADD` to download a .NET installer.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Combined with multi-stage builds, only the .NET runtime remains in the final stage, no intermediate files.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The best use for `ENTRYPOINT` is to set the image's main command, allowing that image to be run as though it was that command, and then use `CMD` as the default flags.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This is useful because the image name can double as a reference to the binary as shown in the command above.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The `ENTRYPOINT` instruction can also be used in combination with a helper script, allowing it to function in a similar way to the command above, even when starting the tool may require more than one step.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This script uses the `exec` builtin so that the final running application becomes the container's PID 1.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This allows the application to receive any Unix signals sent to the container.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For more information, see the `ENTRYPOINT` reference.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] This script lets you interact with Postgres in several ways.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For more information about `ENTRYPOINT`, see Dockerfile reference for the ENTRYPOINT instruction.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] You should use the `VOLUME` instruction to expose any database storage area, configuration storage, or files and folders created by your Docker container.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] You are strongly encouraged to use `VOLUME` for any combination of mutable or user-serviceable parts of your image.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For more information about `VOLUME`, see Dockerfile reference for the VOLUME instruction.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] If a service can run without privileges, use `USER` to change to a non-root user.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Avoid installing or using `sudo` as it has unpredictable TTY and signal-forwarding behavior that can cause problems.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] If you absolutely need functionality similar to `sudo`, such as initializing the daemon as `root` but running it as non-`root`, consider using “gosu”.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Lastly, to reduce layers and complexity, avoid switching `USER` back and forth frequently.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For more information about `USER`, see Dockerfile reference for the USER instruction.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For clarity and reliability, you should always use absolute paths for your `WORKDIR`.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Also, you should use `WORKDIR` instead of proliferating instructions like `RUN cd … && do-something`, which are hard to read, troubleshoot, and maintain.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For more information about `WORKDIR`, see Dockerfile reference for the `WORKDIR` instruction.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] An `ONBUILD` command executes after the current Dockerfile build completes.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] `ONBUILD` executes in any child image derived `FROM` the current image.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Think of the `ONBUILD` command as an instruction that the parent Dockerfile gives to the child Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] A Docker build executes `ONBUILD` commands before any command in a child Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] `ONBUILD` is useful for images that are going to be built `FROM` a given image.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For example, you would use `ONBUILD` for a language stack image that builds arbitrary user software written in that language within the Dockerfile, as you can see in Ruby’s `ONBUILD` variants.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Images built with `ONBUILD` should get a separate tag.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Be careful when putting `ADD` or `COPY` in `ONBUILD`.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] The image fails catastrophically if the new build's context is missing the resource being added.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] Adding a separate tag, as recommended above, helps mitigate this by allowing the Dockerfile author to make a choice.
[src:docker-containers/best-practices] For more information about `ONBUILD`, see Dockerfile reference for the ONBUILD instruction.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker is an open platform for developing, shipping, and running applications.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker enables you to separate your applications from your infrastructure so you can deliver software quickly.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] With Docker, you can manage your infrastructure in the same ways you manage your applications.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] By taking advantage of Docker's methodologies for shipping, testing, and deploying code, you can significantly reduce the delay between writing code and running it in production.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker provides the ability to package and run an application in a loosely isolated environment called a container.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] The isolation and security let you run many containers simultaneously on a given host.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Containers are lightweight and contain everything needed to run the application, so you don't need to rely on what's installed on the host.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] You can share containers while you work, and be sure that everyone you share with gets the same container that works in the same way.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker streamlines the development lifecycle by allowing developers to work in standardized environments using local containers which provide your applications and services.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Containers are great for continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD) workflows.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker's container-based platform allows for highly portable workloads.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker containers can run on a developer's local laptop, on physical or virtual machines in a data center, on cloud providers, or in a mixture of environments.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker's portability and lightweight nature also make it easy to dynamically manage workloads, scaling up or tearing down applications and services as business needs dictate, in near real time.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] It provides a viable, cost-effective alternative to hypervisor-based virtual machines, so you can use more of your server capacity to achieve your business goals.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker is perfect for high density environments and for small and medium deployments where you need to do more with fewer resources.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker uses a client-server architecture.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] The Docker client talks to the Docker daemon, which does the heavy lifting of building, running, and distributing your Docker containers.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] The Docker client and daemon can run on the same system, or you can connect a Docker client to a remote Docker daemon.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] The Docker client and daemon communicate using a REST API, over UNIX sockets or a network interface.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Another Docker client is Docker Compose, that lets you work with applications consisting of a set of containers.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] The Docker daemon (`dockerd`) listens for Docker API requests and manages Docker objects such as images, containers, networks, and volumes.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] A daemon can also communicate with other daemons to manage Docker services.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] The Docker client (`docker`) is the primary way that many Docker users interact with Docker.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] When you use commands such as `docker run`, the client sends these commands to `dockerd`, which carries them out.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] The `docker` command uses the Docker API.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] The Docker client can communicate with more than one daemon.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker Desktop is an easy-to-install application for your Mac, Windows, or Linux environment that enables you to build and share containerized applications and microservices.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker Desktop includes the Docker daemon (`dockerd`), the Docker client (`docker`), Docker Compose, Docker Content Trust, Kubernetes, and Credential Helper.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] For more information, see Docker Desktop.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker Hub is a public registry that anyone can use, and Docker looks for images on Docker Hub by default.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] You can even run your own private registry.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] When you use the `docker pull` or `docker run` commands, Docker pulls the required images from your configured registry.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] When you use the `docker push` command, Docker pushes your image to your configured registry.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] When you use Docker, you are creating and using images, containers, networks, volumes, plugins, and other objects.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] This section is a brief overview of some of those objects.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] An image is a read-only template with instructions for creating a Docker container.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Often, an image is based on another image, with some additional customization.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] For example, you may build an image that is based on the Ubuntu image but includes the Apache web server and your application, as well as the configuration details needed to make your application run.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] You might create your own images or you might only use those created by others and published in a registry.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] To build your own image, you create a Dockerfile with a simple syntax for defining the steps needed to create the image and run it.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Each instruction in a Dockerfile creates a layer in the image.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] When you change the Dockerfile and rebuild the image, only those layers which have changed are rebuilt.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] This is part of what makes images so lightweight, small, and fast, when compared to other virtualization technologies.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] A container is a runnable instance of an image.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] You can create, start, stop, move, or delete a container using the Docker API or CLI.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] You can connect a container to one or more networks, attach storage to it, or even create a new image based on its current state.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] By default, a container is relatively well isolated from other containers and its host machine.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] You can control how isolated a container's network, storage, or other underlying subsystems are from other containers or from the host machine.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] A container is defined by its image as well as any configuration options you provide to it when you create or start it.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] When a container is removed, any changes to its state that aren't stored in persistent storage disappear.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] The following command runs an `ubuntu` container, attaches interactively to your local command-line session, and runs `/bin/bash`.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker creates a new container, as though you had run a `docker container create` command manually.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker allocates a read-write filesystem to the container, as its final layer.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] This allows a running container to create or modify files and directories in its local filesystem.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker creates a network interface to connect the container to the default network, since you didn't specify any networking options.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] This includes assigning an IP address to the container.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] By default, containers can connect to external networks using the host machine's network connection.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker starts the container and executes `/bin/bash`.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Because the container is running interactively and attached to your terminal (due to the `-i` and `-t` flags), you can provide input using your keyboard while Docker logs the output to your terminal.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] When you run `exit` to terminate the `/bin/bash` command, the container stops but isn't removed.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker is written in the Go programming language and takes advantage of several features of the Linux kernel to deliver its functionality.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Docker uses a technology called `namespaces` to provide the isolated workspace called the container.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] When you run a container, Docker creates a set of namespaces for that container.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] These namespaces provide a layer of isolation.
[src:docker-containers/docker-overview] Each aspect of a container runs in a separate namespace and its access is limited to that namespace.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Container networking refers to the ability for containers to connect to and communicate with each other, and with non-Docker network services.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Containers have networking enabled by default, and they can make outgoing connections.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] A container has no information about what kind of network it's attached to, or whether its network peers are also Docker containers.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] A container only sees a network interface with an IP address, a gateway, a routing table, DNS services, and other networking details.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] This page describes networking from the point of view of the container, and the concepts around container networking.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] When Docker Engine on Linux starts for the first time, it has a single built-in network called the "default bridge" network.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] When you run a container without the `--network` option, it is connected to the default bridge.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Containers attached to the default bridge have access to network services outside the Docker host.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] They use "masquerading" which means, if the Docker host has Internet access, no additional configuration is needed for the container to have Internet access.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] With the default configuration, containers attached to the default bridge network have unrestricted network access to each other using container IP addresses.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] They cannot refer to each other by name.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] It can be useful to separate groups of containers that should have full access to each other, but restricted access to containers in other groups.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] You can create custom, user-defined networks, and connect groups of containers to the same network.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Once connected to a user-defined network, containers can communicate with each other using container IP addresses or container names.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Docker Engine has a number of network drivers, as well as the default "bridge".
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] More information can be found in the network driver specific pages, including their configuration options and details about their functionality.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Native Windows containers have a different set of drivers, see Windows container network drivers.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Connecting a container to a network can be compared to connecting an Ethernet cable to a physical host.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Just as a host can be connected to multiple Ethernet networks, a container can be connected to multiple Docker networks.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] For example, a frontend container may be connected to a bridge network with external access, and a `--internal` network to communicate with containers running backend services that do not need external network access.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] A container may also be connected to different types of network.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] For example, an `ipvlan` network to provide internet access, and a `bridge` network for access to local services.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Containers can also share networking stacks, see Container networks.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] When sending packets, if the destination is an address in a directly connected network, packets are sent to that network.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Otherwise, packets are sent to a default gateway for routing to their destination.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] In the example above, the `ipvlan` network's gateway must be the default gateway.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] The default gateway is selected by Docker, and may change whenever a container's network connections change.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] To make Docker choose a specific default gateway when creating the container or connecting a new network, set a gateway priority.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] See option `gw-priority` for the `docker run` and `docker network connect` commands.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] The default `gw-priority` is `0` and the gateway in the network with the highest priority is the default gateway.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] So, when a network should always be the default gateway, it is enough to set its `gw-priority` to `1`.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] When you create or run a container using `docker create` or `docker run`, all ports of containers on bridge networks are accessible from the Docker host and other containers connected to the same network.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Ports are not accessible from outside the host or, with the default configuration, from containers in other networks.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Use the `--publish` or `-p` flag to make a port available outside the host, and to containers in other bridge networks.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] For more information about port mapping, including how to disable it and use direct routing to containers, see port publishing.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] When creating a network, IPv4 address allocation is enabled by default, it can be disabled using `--ipv4=false`.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] IPv6 address allocation can be enabled using `--ipv6`.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] By default, the container gets an IP address for every Docker network it attaches to.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] A container receives an IP address out of the IP subnet of the network.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] The Docker daemon performs dynamic subnetting and IP address allocation for containers.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Each network also has a default subnet mask and gateway.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] You can connect a running container to multiple networks, either by passing the `--network` flag multiple times when creating the container, or using the `docker network connect` command for already running containers.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] In both cases, you can use the `--ip` or `--ip6` flags to specify the container's IP address on that particular network.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] In the same way, a container's hostname defaults to be the container's ID in Docker.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] You can override the hostname using `--hostname`.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] When connecting to an existing network using `docker network connect`, you can use the `--alias` flag to specify an additional network alias for the container on that network.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Docker networks can use either explicitly configured subnets or automatically allocated ones from default pools.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] When no `--subnet` option is provided, Docker automatically selects a subnet from predefined "default address pools".
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] These pools can be configured in `/etc/docker/daemon.json`.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] When an IPv6 subnet is required and there are no IPv6 addresses in `default-address-pools`, Docker allocates subnets from a Unique Local Address (ULA) prefix.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] To use specific IPv6 subnets instead, add them to your `default-address-pools`.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] See Dynamic IPv6 subnet allocation for more information.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Docker attempts to avoid address prefixes already in use on the host.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] However, you may need to customize `default-address-pools` to prevent routing conflicts in some network environments.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] The default pools use large subnets, which limits the number of networks you can create.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] You can divide base subnets into smaller pools to support more networks.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] For example, this configuration allows Docker to create 256 networks from `172.17.0.0/16`.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Containers use the same DNS servers as the host by default, but you can override this with `--dns`.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] By default, containers inherit the DNS settings as defined in the `/etc/resolv.conf` configuration file.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Containers that attach to the default `bridge` network receive a copy of this file.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Containers that attach to a custom network use Docker's embedded DNS server.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] The embedded DNS server forwards external DNS lookups to the DNS servers configured on the host.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] The embedded DNS server address is `127.0.0.11`.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] There is no IPv6 equivalent; the IPv4 address works even in IPv6-only containers.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] If an application requires an explicit DNS server address, use `127.0.0.11`.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] You can configure DNS resolution on a per-container basis, using flags for the `docker run` or `docker create` command used to start the container.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] The following table describes the available `docker run` flags related to DNS configuration.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Your container will have lines in `/etc/hosts` which define the hostname of the container itself, as well as `localhost` and a few other common things.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] Custom hosts, defined in `/etc/hosts` on the host machine, aren't inherited by containers.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] To pass additional hosts into a container, refer to add entries to container hosts file in the `docker run` reference documentation.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] In addition to user-defined networks, you can attach a container to another container's networking stack directly, using the `--network container:<name|id>` flag format.
[src:docker-containers/engine-network] The following example runs a Redis container, with Redis binding to 127.0.0.1, then running the `redis-cli` command and connecting to the Redis server over 127.0.0.1.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:docker-containers/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Docker can build images automatically by reading the instructions from a Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] A Dockerfile is a text document that contains all the commands a user could call on the command line to assemble an image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] This page describes the commands you can use in a Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] However, convention is for them to be UPPERCASE to distinguish them from arguments more easily.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Docker runs instructions in a Dockerfile in order.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] A Dockerfile **must begin with a `FROM` instruction**.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] This may be after parser directives, comments, and globally scoped ARGs.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The `FROM` instruction specifies the base image from which you are building.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] `FROM` may only be preceded by one or more `ARG` instructions, which declare arguments that are used in `FROM` lines in the Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] BuildKit treats lines that begin with `#` as a comment, unless the line is a valid parser directive.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] A `#` marker anywhere else in a line is treated as an argument.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Comment lines are removed before the Dockerfile instructions are executed.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The comment in the following example is removed before the shell executes the `echo` command.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Comments don't support line continuation characters.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Parser directives are optional, and affect the way in which subsequent lines in a Dockerfile are handled.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Parser directives don't add layers to the build, and don't show up as build steps.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Parser directives are written as a special type of comment in the form `# directive=value`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] A single directive may only be used once.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Once a comment, empty line or builder instruction has been processed, BuildKit no longer looks for parser directives.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Instead it treats anything formatted as a parser directive as a comment and doesn't attempt to validate if it might be a parser directive.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Therefore, all parser directives must be at the top of a Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Parser directive keys, such as `syntax` or `check`, aren't case-sensitive, but they're lowercase by convention.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Values for a directive are case-sensitive and must be written in the appropriate case for the directive.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] For example, `#check=skip=jsonargsrecommended` is invalid because the check name must use Pascal case, not lowercase.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] It's also conventional to include a blank line following any parser directives.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Line continuation characters aren't supported in parser directives.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The following `unknowndirective` is treated as a comment because it isn't recognized.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The known `syntax` directive is treated as a comment because it appears after a comment that isn't a parser directive.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Non line-breaking whitespace is permitted in a parser directive.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Use the `syntax` parser directive to declare the Dockerfile syntax version to use for the build.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] If unspecified, BuildKit uses a bundled version of the Dockerfile frontend.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Declaring a syntax version lets you automatically use the latest Dockerfile version without having to upgrade BuildKit or Docker Engine, or even use a custom Dockerfile implementation.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Most users will want to set this parser directive to `docker/dockerfile:1`, which causes BuildKit to pull the latest stable version of the Dockerfile syntax before the build.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] For more information about how the parser directive works, see Custom Dockerfile syntax.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The `escape` directive sets the character used to escape characters in a Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] If not specified, the default escape character is `\`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The escape character is used both to escape characters in a line, and to escape a newline.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] This allows a Dockerfile instruction to span multiple lines.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Note that regardless of whether the `escape` parser directive is included in a Dockerfile, escaping is not performed in a `RUN` command, except at the end of a line.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Setting the escape character to ` is especially useful on `Windows`, where `\` is the directory path separator.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] ` is consistent with Windows PowerShell.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Consider the following example which would fail in a non-obvious way on Windows.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The second `\` at the end of the second line would be interpreted as an escape for the newline, instead of a target of the escape from the first `\`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Similarly, the `\` at the end of the third line would, assuming it was actually handled as an instruction, cause it be treated as a line continuation.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] One solution to the above would be to use `/` as the target of both the `COPY` instruction, and `dir`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] However, this syntax is, at best, confusing as it is not natural for paths on Windows, and at worst, error prone as not all commands on Windows support `/` as the path separator.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The `check` directive is used to configure how build checks are evaluated.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] By default, all checks are run, and failures are treated as warnings.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] You can disable specific checks using `#check=skip=<check-name>`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] To disable all checks, use `#check=skip=all`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] By default, builds with failing build checks exit with a zero status code despite warnings.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] To make the build fail on warnings, set `#check=error=true`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] To see all available checks, see the build checks reference.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Note that the checks available depend on the Dockerfile syntax version.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] To make sure you're getting the most up-to-date checks, use the `syntax` directive to specify the Dockerfile syntax version to the latest stable version.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Environment variables (declared with the `ENV` statement) can also be used in certain instructions as variables to be interpreted by the Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Escapes are also handled for including variable-like syntax into a statement literally.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Environment variables are notated in the Dockerfile either with `$variable_name` or `${variable_name}`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] They are treated equivalently and the brace syntax is typically used to address issues with variable names with no whitespace, like `${foo}_bar`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] In all cases, `word` can be any string, including additional environment variables.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] `pattern` is a glob pattern where `?` matches any single character and `*` any number of characters (including zero).
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] To match literal `?` and `*`, use a backslash escape: `\?` and `\*`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] You can escape whole variable names by adding a `\` before the variable: `\$foo` or `\${foo}`, for example, will translate to `$foo` and `${foo}` literals respectively.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] You can also use environment variables with `RUN`, `CMD`, and `ENTRYPOINT` instructions, but in those cases the variable substitution is handled by the command shell, not the builder.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Note that instructions using the exec form don't invoke a command shell automatically.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Environment variable substitution use the same value for each variable throughout the entire instruction.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Changing the value of a variable only takes effect in subsequent instructions.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] You can use `.dockerignore` file to exclude files and directories from the build context.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] For more information, see .dockerignore file.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The exec form makes it possible to avoid shell string munging, and to invoke commands using a specific command shell, or any other executable.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] It uses a JSON array syntax, where each element in the array is a command, flag, or argument.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The shell form is more relaxed, and emphasizes ease of use, flexibility, and readability.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The shell form automatically uses a command shell, whereas the exec form does not.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The exec form is parsed as a JSON array, which means that you must use double-quotes (") around words, not single-quotes (').
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The exec form is best used to specify an `ENTRYPOINT` instruction, combined with `CMD` for setting default arguments that can be overridden at runtime.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Using the exec form doesn't automatically invoke a command shell.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] This means that normal shell processing, such as variable substitution, doesn't happen.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] For example, `RUN [ "echo", "$HOME" ]` won't handle variable substitution for `$HOME`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] If you want shell processing then either use the shell form or execute a shell directly with the exec form, for example: `RUN [ "sh", "-c", "echo $HOME" ]`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] When using the exec form and executing a shell directly, as in the case for the shell form, it's the shell that's doing the environment variable substitution, not the builder.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] In exec form, you must escape backslashes.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] This is particularly relevant on Windows where the backslash is the path separator.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Unlike the exec form, instructions using the shell form always use a command shell.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The shell form doesn't use the JSON array format, instead it's a regular string.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The shell form string lets you escape newlines using the escape character (backslash by default) to continue a single instruction onto the next line.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] This makes it easier to use with longer commands, because it lets you split them up into multiple lines.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] You can also use heredocs with the shell form to break up supported commands.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] For more information about heredocs, see Here-documents.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] You can change the default shell using the `SHELL` command.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The `FROM` instruction initializes a new build stage and sets the base image for subsequent instructions.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] As such, a valid Dockerfile must start with a `FROM` instruction.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The optional `--platform` flag can be used to specify the platform of the image in case `FROM` references a multi-platform image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] By default, the target platform of the build request is used.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Global build arguments can be used in the value of this flag, for example automatic platform ARGs allow you to force a stage to native build platform (`--platform=$BUILDPLATFORM`), and use it to cross-compile to the target platform inside the stage.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] `FROM` instructions support variables that are declared by any `ARG` instructions that occur before the first `FROM`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] An `ARG` declared before a `FROM` is outside of a build stage, so it can't be used in any instruction after a `FROM`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The `RUN` instruction will execute any commands to create a new layer on top of the current image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The added layer is used in the next step in the Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] For more information about the differences between these two forms, see shell or exec forms.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The cache for `RUN` instructions isn't invalidated automatically during the next build.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The cache for an instruction like `RUN apt-get dist-upgrade -y` will be reused during the next build.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The cache for `RUN` instructions can be invalidated by using the `--no-cache` flag, for example `docker build --no-cache`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] See the Dockerfile Best Practices guide for more information.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The cache for `RUN` instructions can be invalidated by `ADD` and `COPY` instructions.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] `RUN --device` allows build to request CDI devices to be available to the build step.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The device `name` is provided by the CDI specification registered in BuildKit.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] In the following example, multiple devices are registered in the CDI specification for the `vendor1.com/device` vendor.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] `RUN --mount` allows you to create filesystem mounts that the build can access.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] This mount type allows binding files or directories to the build container.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] This mount type allows the build container to cache directories for compilers and package managers.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Contents of the cache directories persists between builder invocations without invalidating the instruction cache.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Cache mounts should only be used for better performance.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Your build should work with any contents of the cache directory as another build may overwrite the files or GC may clean it if more storage space is needed.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Apt needs exclusive access to its data, so the caches use the option `sharing=locked`, which will make sure multiple parallel builds using the same cache mount will wait for each other and not access the same cache files at the same time.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] You could also use `sharing=private` if you prefer to have each build create another cache directory in this case.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] This mount type allows mounting `tmpfs` in the build container.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] This mount type allows the build container to access secret values, such as tokens or private keys, without baking them into the image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] By default, the secret is mounted as a file.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] You can also mount the secret as an environment variable by setting the `env` option.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The following example takes the secret `API_KEY` and mounts it as an environment variable with the same name.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] This mount type allows the build container to access SSH keys via SSH agents, with support for passphrases.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] You can also specify a path to `*.pem` file on the host directly instead of `$SSH_AUTH_SOCK`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] However, pem files with passphrases are not supported.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] `RUN --network` allows control over which networking environment the command is run in.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Equivalent to not supplying a flag at all, the command is run in the default network for the build.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] `pip` will only be able to install the packages provided in the tarfile, which can be controlled by an earlier build stage.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] With `--security=insecure`, the builder runs the command without sandbox in insecure mode, which allows to run flows requiring elevated privileges (e.g. containerd).
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] This is equivalent to running `docker run --privileged`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Default sandbox mode can be activated via `--security=sandbox`, but that is no-op.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The `CMD` instruction sets the command to be executed when running a container from an image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] There can only be one `CMD` instruction in a Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] If you list more than one `CMD`, only the last one takes effect.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The purpose of a `CMD` is to provide defaults for an executing container.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] These defaults can include an executable, or they can omit the executable, in which case you must specify an `ENTRYPOINT` instruction as well.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] If you would like your container to run the same executable every time, then you should consider using `ENTRYPOINT` in combination with `CMD`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] If the user specifies arguments to `docker run` then they will override the default specified in `CMD`, but still use the default `ENTRYPOINT`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] If `CMD` is used to provide default arguments for the `ENTRYPOINT` instruction, both the `CMD` and `ENTRYPOINT` instructions should be specified in the exec form.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The `LABEL` instruction adds metadata to an image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] To include spaces within a `LABEL` value, use quotes and backslashes as you would in command-line parsing.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] You can specify multiple labels on a single line.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Prior to Docker 1.10, this decreased the size of the final image, but this is no longer the case.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Labels included in base images (images in the `FROM` line) are inherited by your image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] If a label already exists but with a different value, the most-recently-applied value overrides any previously-set value.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] In a multi-stage build, labels from intermediate stages are only present in the final image if the final stage is directly or indirectly based on them (via `FROM`).
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Labels from a stage that you only reference with `COPY --from` or `RUN --mount=from=` are not included in the output image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Labels from the base image specified in the final `FROM` instruction are always inherited.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] To view an image's labels, use the `docker image inspect` command.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The `MAINTAINER` instruction sets the *Author* field of the generated images.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The `LABEL` instruction is a much more flexible version of this and you should use it instead, as it enables setting any metadata you require, and can be viewed easily, for example with `docker inspect`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] This will then be visible from `docker inspect` with the other labels.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The `EXPOSE` instruction informs Docker that the container listens on the specified network ports at runtime.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] You can specify whether the port listens on TCP or UDP, and the default is TCP if you don't specify a protocol.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The `EXPOSE` instruction doesn't actually publish the port.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] It functions as a type of documentation between the person who builds the image and the person who runs the container, about which ports are intended to be published.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] To publish the port when running the container, use the `-p` flag on `docker run` to publish and map one or more ports, or the `-P` flag to publish all exposed ports and map them to high-order ports.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] In this case, if you use `-P` with `docker run`, the port will be exposed once for TCP and once for UDP.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Remember that `-P` uses an ephemeral high-ordered host port on the host, so TCP and UDP doesn't use the same port.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Regardless of the `EXPOSE` settings, you can override them at runtime by using the `-p` flag.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] To set up port redirection on the host system, see using the -P flag.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The `docker network` command supports creating networks for communication among containers without the need to expose or publish specific ports, because the containers connected to the network can communicate with each other over any port.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] For detailed information, see the overview of this feature.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The `ENV` instruction sets the environment variable `<key>` to the value `<value>`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] This value will be in the environment for all subsequent instructions in the build stage and can be replaced inline in many as well.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The value will be interpreted for other environment variables, so quote characters will be removed if they are not escaped.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Like command line parsing, quotes and backslashes can be used to include spaces within values.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] The environment variables set using `ENV` will persist when a container is run from the resulting image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] You can view the values using `docker inspect`, and change them using `docker run --env <key>=<value>`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] A stage inherits any environment variables that were set using `ENV` by its parent stage or any ancestor.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Refer to the multi-stage builds section in the manual for more information.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] Environment variable persistence can cause unexpected side effects.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p01] For example, setting `ENV DEBIAN_FRONTEND=noninteractive` changes the behavior of `apt-get`, and may confuse users of your image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The latter form is required for paths containing whitespace.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `ADD` instruction copies new files or directories from `<src>` and adds them to the filesystem of the image at the path `<dest>`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Files and directories can be copied from the build context, a remote URL, or a Git repository.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `ADD` and `COPY` instructions are functionally similar, but serve slightly different purposes.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Learn more about the differences between `ADD` and `COPY`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] You can specify multiple source files or directories with `ADD`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The last argument must always be the destination.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If you specify multiple source files, either directly or using a wildcard, then the destination must be a directory (must end with a slash `/`).
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] To add files from a remote location, you can specify a URL or the address of a Git repository as the source.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] BuildKit detects the type of `<src>` and processes it accordingly.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Any relative or local path that doesn't begin with a `http://`, `https://`, or `git@` protocol prefix is considered a local file path.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The local file path is relative to the build context.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] For example, if the build context is the current directory, `ADD file.txt /` adds the file at `./file.txt` to the root of the filesystem in the build container.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Specifying a source path with a leading slash or one that navigates outside the build context, such as `ADD ../something /something`, automatically removes any parent directory navigation (`../`).
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Trailing slashes in the source path are also disregarded, making `ADD something/ /something` equivalent to `ADD something /something`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If the source is a directory, the contents of the directory are copied, including filesystem metadata.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The directory itself isn't copied, only its contents.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If it contains subdirectories, these are also copied, and merged with any existing directories at the destination.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Any conflicts are resolved in favor of the content being added, on a file-by-file basis, except if you're trying to copy a directory onto an existing file, in which case an error is raised.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If the source is a file, the file and its metadata are copied to the destination.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If the source is a file and a directory with the same name exists at the destination, an error is raised.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If you pass a Dockerfile through stdin to the build (`docker build - < Dockerfile`), there is no build context.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] In this case, you can only use the `ADD` instruction to copy remote files.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] You can also pass a tar archive through stdin: (`docker build - < archive.tar`), the Dockerfile at the root of the archive and the rest of the archive will be used as the context of the build.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] For local files, each `<src>` may contain wildcards and matching will be done using Go's filepath.Match rules.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] In the following example, `?` is a single-character wildcard, matching e.g.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] When adding files or directories that contain special characters (such as `[` and `]`), you need to escape those paths following the Golang rules to prevent them from being treated as a matching pattern.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] When using a local tar archive as the source for `ADD`, and the archive is in a recognized compression format (`gzip`, `bzip2` or `xz`, or uncompressed), the archive is decompressed and extracted into the specified destination.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Local tar archives are extracted by default, see the [`ADD --unpack` flag].
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] When a directory is extracted, it has the same behavior as `tar -x`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The contents of the source tree, with conflicts resolved in favor of the content being added, on a file-by-file basis.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] In the case where source is a remote file URL, the destination will have permissions of 600.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If the HTTP response contains a `Last-Modified` header, the timestamp from that header will be used to set the `mtime` on the destination file.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] However, like any other file processed during an `ADD`, `mtime` isn't included in the determination of whether or not the file has changed and the cache should be updated.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If remote file is a tar archive, the archive is not extracted by default.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] To download and extract the archive, use the [`ADD --unpack` flag].
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If the destination ends with a trailing slash, then the filename is inferred from the URL path.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] For example, `ADD http://example.com/foobar /` would create the file `/foobar`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The URL must have a nontrivial path so that an appropriate filename can be discovered (`http://example.com` doesn't work).
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If the destination doesn't end with a trailing slash, the destination path becomes the filename of the file downloaded from the URL.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] For example, `ADD http://example.com/foo /bar` creates the file `/bar`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If your URL files are protected using authentication, you need to use `RUN wget`, `RUN curl` or use another tool from within the container as the `ADD` instruction doesn't support authentication.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] You can use the `HTTP_AUTH_HEADER_<host>` and `HTTP_AUTH_TOKEN_<host>` secrets to set credentials for remote sources.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] For more information, see Build secrets.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] To use a Git repository as the source for `ADD`, you can reference the repository's HTTP or SSH address as the source.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The repository is cloned to the specified destination in the image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] You can use URL fragments to specify a specific branch, tag, commit, or subdirectory.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] For more information about Git URL fragments, see URL fragments.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] When adding from a Git repository, the permissions bits for files are 644.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If a file in the repository has the executable bit set, it will have permissions set to 755.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Directories have permissions set to 755.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] When using a Git repository as the source, the repository must be accessible from the build context.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] To add a repository via SSH, whether public or private, you must pass an SSH key for authentication.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] To build this Dockerfile, pass the `--ssh` flag to the `docker build` to mount the SSH agent socket to the build.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] For more information about building with secrets, see Build secrets.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If the destination path begins with a forward slash, it's interpreted as an absolute path, and the source files are copied into the specified destination relative to the root of the current build stage.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] For example, `ADD test.txt /abs` creates a file at `/abs`, whereas `ADD test.txt /abs/` creates `/abs/test.txt`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If the destination path doesn't begin with a leading slash, it's interpreted as relative to the working directory of the build container.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If destination doesn't exist, it's created, along with all missing directories in its path.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If the source is a file, and the destination doesn't end with a trailing slash, the source file will be written to the destination path as a file.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] When `<src>` is the HTTP or SSH address of a remote Git repository, BuildKit adds the contents of the Git repository to the image excluding the `.git` directory by default.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `--keep-git-dir=true` flag lets you preserve the `.git` directory.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `--unpack` flag controls whether or not to automatically unpack tar archives (including compressed formats like `gzip` or `bzip2`) when adding them to the image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Local tar archives are unpacked by default, whereas remote tar archives (where `src` is a URL) are downloaded without unpacking.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `COPY` instruction copies new files or directories from `<src>` and adds them to the filesystem of the image at the path `<dest>`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Files and directories can be copied from the build context, build stage, named context, or an image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] You can specify multiple source files or directories with `COPY`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] `COPY` accepts a flag `--from=<name>` that lets you specify the source location to be a build stage, context, or image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] For more information about copying from named sources, see the `--from` flag.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] When copying source files from the build context, paths are interpreted as relative to the root of the context.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Specifying a source path with a leading slash or one that navigates outside the build context, such as `COPY ../something /something`, automatically removes any parent directory navigation (`../`).
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Trailing slashes in the source path are also disregarded, making `COPY something/ /something` equivalent to `COPY something /something`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] In this case, you can only use the `COPY` instruction to copy files from other stages, named contexts, or images, using the `--from` flag.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] When using a Git repository as the build context, the permissions bits for copied files are 644.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] For example, `COPY test.txt /abs` creates a file at `/abs`, whereas `COPY test.txt /abs/` creates `/abs/test.txt`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] By default, the `COPY` instruction copies files from the build context.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `COPY --from` flag lets you copy files from an image, a build stage, or a named context instead.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] To copy from a build stage in a multi-stage build, specify the name of the stage you want to copy from.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] You specify stage names using the `AS` keyword with the `FROM` instruction.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] You can also copy files directly from named contexts (specified with `--build-context <name>=<source>`) or images.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The following example copies an `nginx.conf` file from the official Nginx image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The source path of `COPY --from` is always resolved from filesystem root of the image or stage that you specify.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Symbolic notation (added in Dockerfile version 1.14) is useful when octal isn't flexible enough.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] For example, `u=rwX,go=rX` sets directories to 755 and files to 644, while preserving the executable bit on files that already have it.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] For more information about symbolic notation syntax, see the chmod(1) manual.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `--chmod` flag is not supported when building Windows containers.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Without this flag, files are created with UID and GID of 0.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The flag accepts usernames, group names, UIDs, or GIDs in any combination.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If you specify only a user, the GID is set to the same numeric value as the UID.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] When using names instead of numeric IDs, BuildKit resolves them using `/etc/passwd` and `/etc/group` in the container's root filesystem.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If these files are missing or don't contain the specified names, the build fails.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `--chown` flag is not supported when building Windows containers.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Enabling this flag in `COPY` or `ADD` commands allows you to copy files with enhanced semantics where your files remain independent on their own layer and don't get invalidated when commands on previous layers are changed.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] When `--link` is used your source files are copied into an empty destination directory.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] That directory is turned into a layer that is linked on top of your previous state.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] and merging all the layers of both images together.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Use `--link` to reuse already built layers in subsequent builds with `--cache-from` even if the previous layers have changed.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] This is especially important for multi-stage builds where a `COPY --from` statement would previously get invalidated if any previous commands in the same stage changed, causing the need to rebuild the intermediate stages again.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] With `--link` the layer the previous build generated is reused and merged on top of the new layers.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] This also means you can easily rebase your images when the base images receive updates, without having to execute the whole build again.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] In backends that support it, BuildKit can do this rebase action without the need to push or pull any layers between the client and the registry.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] BuildKit will detect this case and only create new image manifest that contains the new layers and old layers in correct order.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The same behavior where BuildKit can avoid pulling down the base image can also happen when using `--link` and no other commands that would require access to the files in the base image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] In that case BuildKit will only build the layers for the `COPY` commands and push them to the registry directly on top of the layers of the base image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] When using `--link` the `COPY/ADD` commands are not allowed to read any files from the previous state.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] This means that if in previous state the destination directory was a path that contained a symlink, `COPY/ADD` can not follow it.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] In the final image the destination path created with `--link` will always be a path containing only directories.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If you don't rely on the behavior of following symlinks in the destination path, using `--link` is always recommended.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The performance of `--link` is equivalent or better than the default behavior and, it creates much better conditions for cache reuse.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] When copying a path into a subdirectory, `--link` will always copy from the root of the filesystem.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] When copying a directory, the existing mode is overridden with the new mode from the copied path.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If you need a specific mode for a directory, such as the more permissive `/tmp` directory, you may need to either avoid using `--link`, unroll the copy into its base components, or use `--chmod` to ensure the overwriting directory contains the same permissions.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `--parents` flag preserves parent directories for `src` entries.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] This behavior is similar to the Linux `cp` utility's `--parents` or `rsync` `--relative` flag.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] As with Rsync, it is possible to limit which parent directories are preserved by inserting a dot and a slash (`./`) into the source path.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If such point exists, only parent directories after it will be preserved.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] This may be especially useful copies between stages with `--from` where the source paths need to be absolute.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Note that, without the `--parents` flag specified, any filename collision will fail the Linux `cp` operation with an explicit error message (`cp: will not overwrite just-created './x/a.txt' with './y/a.txt'`), where the Buildkit will silently overwrite the target file at the destination.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] While it is possible to preserve the directory structure for `COPY` instructions consisting of only one `src` entry, usually it is more beneficial to keep the layer count in the resulting image as low as possible.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Therefore, with the `--parents` flag, the Buildkit is capable of packing multiple `COPY` instructions together, keeping the directory structure intact.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `--exclude` flag lets you specify a path expression for files to be excluded.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The path expression follows the same format as `<src>`, supporting wildcards and matching using Go's filepath.Match rules.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] You can specify the `--exclude` option multiple times for a `COPY` instruction.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Files matching any of the specified `--exclude` patterns are not copied, even if their paths match the pattern specified in `<src>`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] An `ENTRYPOINT` allows you to configure a container that will run as an executable.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] For more information about the different forms, see Shell and exec form.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Command line arguments to `docker run <image>` will be appended after all elements in an exec form `ENTRYPOINT`, and will override all elements specified using `CMD`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] This allows arguments to be passed to the entry point, i.e., `docker run <image> -d` will pass the `-d` argument to the entry point.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] You can override the `ENTRYPOINT` instruction using the `docker run --entrypoint` flag.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The shell form of `ENTRYPOINT` ignores any `CMD` or `docker run` command line arguments.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] It also starts your `ENTRYPOINT` as a subcommand of `/bin/sh -c`, which does not pass signals.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] This means that the executable will not be the container's `PID 1`, and will not receive Unix signals.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] In this case, your executable doesn't receive a `SIGTERM` from `docker stop <container>`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Only the last `ENTRYPOINT` instruction in the Dockerfile will have an effect.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] You can use the exec form of `ENTRYPOINT` to set fairly stable default commands and arguments and then use `CMD` to set additional defaults that are more likely to be changed.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] When combining exec form `ENTRYPOINT` with `CMD`, use the exec form of `CMD` as well.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Using the shell form of `CMD` causes it to be wrapped in `/bin/sh -c`, which means the `ENTRYPOINT` receives a shell invocation as its argument rather than the bare command and parameters.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] See Understand how CMD and ENTRYPOINT interact.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] And you can gracefully request `top` to shut down using `docker stop test`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] You can specify a plain string for the `ENTRYPOINT` and it will execute in `/bin/sh -c`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] This form will use shell processing to substitute shell environment variables, and will ignore any `CMD` or `docker run` command line arguments.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] You can see from the output of `top` that the specified `ENTRYPOINT` is not `PID 1`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Both `CMD` and `ENTRYPOINT` instructions define what command gets executed when running a container.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] There are few rules that describe their co-operation.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] `ENTRYPOINT` should be defined when using the container as an executable.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] `CMD` should be used as a way of defining default arguments for an `ENTRYPOINT` command or for executing an ad-hoc command in a container.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] `CMD` will be overridden when running the container with alternative arguments.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `VOLUME` instruction creates a mount point with the specified name and marks it as holding externally mounted volumes from native host or other containers.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The value can be a JSON array, `VOLUME ["/var/log/"]`, or a plain string with multiple arguments, such as `VOLUME /var/log` or `VOLUME /var/log /var/db`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] For more information/examples and mounting instructions via the Docker client, refer to *Share Directories via Volumes* documentation.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `docker run` command initializes the newly created volume with any data that exists at the specified location within the base image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] This Dockerfile results in an image that causes `docker run` to create a new mount point at `/myvol` and copy the `greeting` file into the newly created volume.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Keep the following things in mind about volumes in the Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `USER` instruction sets the user name (or UID) and optionally the user group (or GID) to use as the default user and group for the remainder of the current stage.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The specified user is used for `RUN` instructions and at runtime runs the relevant `ENTRYPOINT` and `CMD` commands.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `WORKDIR` instruction sets the working directory for any `RUN`, `CMD`, `ENTRYPOINT`, `COPY` and `ADD` instructions that follow it in the Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If the `WORKDIR` doesn't exist, it will be created even if it's not used in any subsequent Dockerfile instruction.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `WORKDIR` instruction can be used multiple times in a Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If a relative path is provided, it will be relative to the path of the previous `WORKDIR` instruction.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The output of the final `pwd` command in this Dockerfile would be `/a/b/c`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] The `WORKDIR` instruction can resolve environment variables previously set using `ENV`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] You can only use environment variables explicitly set in the Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] If not specified, the default working directory is `/`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] In practice, if you aren't building a Dockerfile from scratch (`FROM scratch`), the `WORKDIR` may likely be set by the base image you're using.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p02] Therefore, to avoid unintended operations in unknown directories, it's best practice to set your `WORKDIR` explicitly.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The `ARG` instruction defines a variable that users can pass at build time to the builder with the `docker build` command using the `--build-arg <varname>=<value>` flag.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] This variable can be used in subsequent instructions such as `FROM`, `ENV`, `WORKDIR`, and others using the `${VAR}` or `$VAR` template syntax.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] It is also passed to all subsequent `RUN` instructions as a build-time environment variable.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Unlike `ENV`, an `ARG` variable is not embedded in the image and is not available in the final container.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] A Dockerfile may include one or more `ARG` instructions.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] If an `ARG` instruction has a default value and if there is no value passed at build-time, the builder uses the default.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] An `ARG` variable comes into effect from the line on which it is declared in the Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] An `ARG` variable declared within a build stage is automatically inherited by other stages based on that stage.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Unrelated build stages do not have access to the variable.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] To use an argument in multiple distinct stages, each stage must include the `ARG` instruction, or they must both be based on a shared base stage in the same Dockerfile where the variable is declared.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] For more information, refer to variable scoping.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] You can use an `ARG` or an `ENV` instruction to specify variables that are available to the `RUN` instruction.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Environment variables defined using the `ENV` instruction always override an `ARG` instruction of the same name.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Consider this Dockerfile with an `ENV` and `ARG` instruction.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] In this case, the `RUN` instruction uses `v1.0.0` instead of the `ARG` setting passed by the user:`v2.0.1` This behavior is similar to a shell script where a locally scoped variable overrides the variables passed as arguments or inherited from environment, from its point of definition.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Unlike an `ARG` instruction, `ENV` values are always persisted in the built image.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Using this Dockerfile example, `CONT_IMG_VER` is still persisted in the image but its value would be `v1.0.0` as it is the default set in line 3 by the `ENV` instruction.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The variable expansion technique in this example allows you to pass arguments from the command line and persist them in the final image by leveraging the `ENV` instruction.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Variable expansion is only supported for a limited set of Dockerfile instructions.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Docker has a set of predefined `ARG` variables that you can use without a corresponding `ARG` instruction in the Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] By default, these pre-defined variables are excluded from the output of `docker history`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Excluding them reduces the risk of accidentally leaking sensitive authentication information in an `HTTP_PROXY` variable.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] In this case, the value of the `HTTP_PROXY` variable is not available in the `docker history` and is not cached.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] If you were to change location, and your proxy server changed to `http://user:pass@proxy.sfo.example.com`, a subsequent build does not result in a cache miss.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] When building this Dockerfile, the `HTTP_PROXY` is preserved in the `docker history`, and changing its value invalidates the build cache.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] This feature is only available when using the BuildKit backend.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] BuildKit supports a predefined set of `ARG` variables with information on the platform of the node performing the build (build platform) and on the platform of the resulting image (target platform).
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The target platform can be specified with the `--platform` flag on `docker build`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] These arguments are defined in the global scope so are not automatically available inside build stages or for your `RUN` commands.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] To expose one of these arguments inside the build stage redefine it without value.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] When using a Git context, `.git` dir is not kept on checkouts.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] `ARG` variables are not persisted into the built image as `ENV` variables are.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] However, `ARG` variables do impact the build cache in similar ways.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] If a Dockerfile defines an `ARG` variable whose value is different from a previous build, then a "cache miss" occurs upon its first usage, not its definition.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] In particular, all `RUN` instructions following an `ARG` instruction use the `ARG` variable implicitly (as an environment variable), thus can cause a cache miss.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] All predefined `ARG` variables are exempt from caching unless there is a matching `ARG` statement in the Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] If you specify `--build-arg CONT_IMG_VER=<value>` on the command line, in both cases, the specification on line 2 doesn't cause a cache miss; line 3 does cause a cache miss.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] `ARG CONT_IMG_VER` causes the `RUN` line to be identified as the same as running `CONT_IMG_VER=<value> echo hello`, so if the `<value>` changes, you get a cache miss.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] In this example, the cache miss occurs on line 3.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The miss happens because the variable's value in the `ENV` references the `ARG` variable and that variable is changed through the command line.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] In this example, the `ENV` command causes the image to include the value.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Line 3 doesn't cause a cache miss because the value of `CONT_IMG_VER` is a constant (`hello`).
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] As a result, the environment variables and values used on the `RUN` (line 4) doesn't change between builds.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The `ONBUILD` instruction adds to the image a trigger instruction to be executed at a later time, when the image is used as the base for another build.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The trigger will be executed in the context of the downstream build, as if it had been inserted immediately after the `FROM` instruction in the downstream Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] This is useful if you are building an image which will be used as a base to build other images, for example an application build environment or a daemon which may be customized with user-specific configuration.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] For example, if your image is a reusable Python application builder, it will require application source code to be added in a particular directory, and it might require a build script to be called after that.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] You can't just call `ADD` and `RUN` now, because you don't yet have access to the application source code, and it will be different for each application build.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] You could simply provide application developers with a boilerplate Dockerfile to copy-paste into their application, but that's inefficient, error-prone and difficult to update because it mixes with application-specific code.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The solution is to use `ONBUILD` to register advance instructions to run later, during the next build stage.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] At the end of the build, a list of all triggers is stored in the image manifest, under the key `OnBuild`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] They can be inspected with the `docker inspect` command.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Later the image may be used as a base for a new build, using the `FROM` instruction.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] As part of processing the `FROM` instruction, the downstream builder looks for `ONBUILD` triggers, and executes them in the same order they were registered.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] If any of the triggers fail, the `FROM` instruction is aborted which in turn causes the build to fail.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] If all triggers succeed, the `FROM` instruction completes and the build continues as usual.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Triggers are cleared from the final image after being executed.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] In other words they aren't inherited by "grand-children" builds.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] As of Dockerfile syntax 1.11, you can use `ONBUILD` with instructions that copy or mount files from other stages, images, or build contexts.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] If the source of `from` is a build stage, the stage must be defined in the Dockerfile where `ONBUILD` gets triggered.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] If it's a named context, that context must be passed to the downstream build.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The `STOPSIGNAL` instruction sets the system call signal that will be sent to the container to exit.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] This signal can be a signal name in the format `SIG<NAME>`, for instance `SIGKILL`, or an unsigned number that matches a position in the kernel's syscall table, for instance `9`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The default is `SIGTERM` if not defined.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] `STOPSIGNAL` applies to the signal sent by `docker stop` (and by the Docker daemon when stopping a container).
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] It does not affect signals sent by keyboard shortcuts such as Ctrl+C, which sends `SIGINT` directly to the process regardless of the `STOPSIGNAL` setting.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The image's default stopsignal can be overridden per container, using the `--stop-signal` flag on `docker run` and `docker create`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The `HEALTHCHECK` instruction tells Docker how to test a container to check that it's still working.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] This can detect cases such as a web server stuck in an infinite loop and unable to handle new connections, even though the server process is still running.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] When a container has a healthcheck specified, it has a health status in addition to its normal status.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Whenever a health check passes, it becomes `healthy` (whatever state it was previously in).
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] After a certain number of consecutive failures, it becomes `unhealthy`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The health check will first run **interval** seconds after the container is started, and then again **interval** seconds after each previous check completes.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] During the **start period**, health checks run at **start interval** frequency instead.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] If a single run of the check takes longer than **timeout** seconds then the check is considered to have failed.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The process performing the check is abruptly stopped with a `SIGKILL`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] It takes **retries** consecutive failures of the health check for the container to be considered `unhealthy`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] There can only be one `HEALTHCHECK` instruction in a Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] If you list more than one then only the last `HEALTHCHECK` will take effect.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The command after the `CMD` keyword can be either a shell command (e.g.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] `HEALTHCHECK CMD /bin/check-running`) or an exec array (as with other Dockerfile commands; see e.g.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The command's exit status indicates the health status of the container.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] To help debug failing probes, any output text (UTF-8 encoded) that the command writes on stdout or stderr will be stored in the health status and can be queried with `docker inspect`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Such output should be kept short (only the first 4096 bytes are stored currently).
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] When the health status of a container changes, a `health_status` event is generated with the new status.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The `SHELL` instruction allows the default shell used for the shell form of commands to be overridden.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The `SHELL` instruction must be written in JSON form in a Dockerfile.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The `SHELL` instruction is particularly useful on Windows where there are two commonly used and quite different native shells: `cmd` and `powershell`, as well as alternate shells available including `sh`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The `SHELL` instruction can appear multiple times.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Each `SHELL` instruction overrides all previous `SHELL` instructions, and affects all subsequent instructions.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The following instructions can be affected by the `SHELL` instruction when the shell form of them is used in a Dockerfile: `RUN`, `CMD` and `ENTRYPOINT`.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] First, there is an unnecessary `cmd.exe` command processor (aka shell) being invoked.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Second, each `RUN` instruction in the shell form requires an extra `powershell -command` prefixing the command.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] To make this more efficient, one of two mechanisms can be employed.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] While the JSON form is unambiguous and does not use the unnecessary `cmd.exe`, it does require more verbosity through double-quoting and escaping.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The `SHELL` instruction could also be used to modify the way in which a shell operates.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] For example, using `SHELL cmd /S /C /V:ON|OFF` on Windows, delayed environment variable expansion semantics could be modified.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The `SHELL` instruction can also be used on Linux should an alternate shell be required such as `zsh`, `csh`, `tcsh` and others.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Here-documents allow redirection of subsequent Dockerfile lines to the input of `RUN` or `COPY` commands.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] If such command contains a here-document the Dockerfile considers the next lines until the line only containing a here-doc delimiter as part of the same command.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] If the command only contains a here-document, its contents is evaluated with the default shell.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Alternatively, shebang header can be used to define an interpreter.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] More complex examples may use multiple here-documents.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] With `COPY` instructions, you can replace the source parameter with a here-doc indicator to write the contents of the here-document directly to a file.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The following example creates a `greeting.txt` file containing `hello world` using a `COPY` instruction.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Regular here-doc variable expansion and tab stripping rules apply.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] The following example shows a small Dockerfile that creates a `hello.sh` script file using a `COPY` instruction with a here-document.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] In this case, file script prints "hello bar", because the variable is expanded when the `COPY` instruction gets executed.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] If instead you were to quote any part of the here-document word `EOT`, the variable would not be expanded at build-time.
[src:docker-containers/reference-dockerfile-p03] Note that `ARG FOO=bar` is excessive here, and can be removed.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Volumes are persistent data stores for containers, created and managed by Docker.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] You can create a volume explicitly using the `docker volume create` command, or Docker can create a volume during container or service creation.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] When you create a volume, it's stored within a directory on the Docker host.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] When you mount the volume into a container, this directory is what's mounted into the container.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] This is similar to the way that bind mounts work, except that volumes are managed by Docker and are isolated from the core functionality of the host machine.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Volumes are the preferred mechanism for persisting data generated by and used by Docker containers.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] While bind mounts are dependent on the directory structure and OS of the host machine, volumes are completely managed by Docker.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Volumes are not a good choice if you need to access the files from the host, as the volume is completely managed by Docker.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Use bind mounts if you need to access files or directories from both containers and the host.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Volumes are often a better choice than writing data directly to a container, because a volume doesn't increase the size of the containers using it.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Using a volume is also faster; writing into a container's writable layer requires a storage driver to manage the filesystem.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The storage driver provides a union filesystem, using the Linux kernel.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] This extra abstraction reduces performance as compared to using volumes, which write directly to the host filesystem.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] If your container generates non-persistent state data, consider using a tmpfs mount to avoid storing the data anywhere permanently, and to increase the container's performance by avoiding writing into the container's writable layer.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Volumes use `rprivate` (recursive private) bind propagation, and bind propagation isn't configurable for volumes.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] A volume's contents exist outside the lifecycle of a given container.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] When a container is destroyed, the writable layer is destroyed with it.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Using a volume ensures that the data is persisted even if the container using it is removed.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] A given volume can be mounted into multiple containers simultaneously.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] When no running container is using a volume, the volume is still available to Docker and isn't removed automatically.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] You can remove unused volumes using `docker volume prune`.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] If you mount a *non-empty volume* into a directory in the container in which files or directories exist, the pre-existing files are obscured by the mount.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] This is similar to if you were to save files into `/mnt` on a Linux host, and then mounted a USB drive into `/mnt`.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The contents of `/mnt` would be obscured by the contents of the USB drive until the USB drive was unmounted.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] With containers, there's no straightforward way of removing a mount to reveal the obscured files again.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Your best option is to recreate the container without the mount.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] If you mount an *empty volume* into a directory in the container in which files or directories exist, these files or directories are propagated (copied) into the volume by default.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Similarly, if you start a container and specify a volume which does not already exist, an empty volume is created for you.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] This is a good way to pre-populate data that another container needs.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] To prevent Docker from copying a container's pre-existing files into an empty volume, use the `volume-nocopy` option, see Options for --mount.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Anonymous volumes are given a random name that's guaranteed to be unique within a given Docker host.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Just like named volumes, anonymous volumes persist even if you remove the container that uses them, except if you use the `--rm` flag when creating the container, in which case the anonymous volume associated with the container is destroyed.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] If you create multiple containers consecutively that each use anonymous volumes, each container creates its own volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Anonymous volumes aren't reused or shared between containers automatically.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] To share an anonymous volume between two or more containers, you must mount the anonymous volume using the random volume ID.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] To mount a volume with the `docker run` command, you can use either the `--mount` or `--volume` flag.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The main difference is that the `--mount` flag is more explicit and supports all the available options.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The `--mount` flag consists of multiple key-value pairs, separated by commas and each consisting of a `<key>=<value>` tuple.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The order of the keys isn't significant.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The `--volume` or `-v` flag consists of three fields, separated by colon characters (`:`).
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The fields must be in the correct order.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] In the case of named volumes, the first field is the name of the volume, and is unique on a given host machine.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] For anonymous volumes, the first field is omitted.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The second field is the path where the file or directory is mounted in the container.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The third field is optional, and is a comma-separated list of options.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Unlike a bind mount, you can create and manage volumes outside the scope of any container.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] If you start a container with a volume that doesn't yet exist, Docker creates the volume for you.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The following example mounts the volume `myvol2` into `/app/` in the container.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The following `-v` and `--mount` examples produce the same result.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] You can't run them both unless you remove the `devtest` container and the `myvol2` volume after running the first one.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Use `docker inspect devtest` to verify that Docker created the volume and it mounted correctly.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] This shows that the mount is a volume, it shows the correct source and destination, and that the mount is read-write.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Stop the container and remove the volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Running `docker compose up` for the first time creates a volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Docker reuses the same volume when you run the command subsequently.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] For more information about using volumes with Compose, refer to the Volumes section in the Compose specification.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] When you start a service and define a volume, each service container uses its own local volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] None of the containers can share this data if you use the `local` volume driver.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] However, some volume drivers do support shared storage.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The following example starts an `nginx` service with four replicas, each of which uses a local volume called `myvol2`.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Removing the service doesn't remove any volumes created by the service.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] If you start a container which creates a new volume, and the container has files or directories in the directory to be mounted such as `/app/`, Docker copies the directory's contents into the volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The container then mounts and uses the volume, and other containers which use the volume also have access to the pre-populated content.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] To show this, the following example starts an `nginx` container and populates the new volume `nginx-vol` with the contents of the container's `/usr/share/nginx/html` directory.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] This is where Nginx stores its default HTML content.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The `--mount` and `-v` examples have the same end result.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] After running either of these examples, run the following commands to clean up the containers and volumes.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] For some development applications, the container needs to write into the bind mount so that changes are propagated back to the Docker host.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] At other times, the container only needs read access to the data.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Multiple containers can mount the same volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] You can simultaneously mount a single volume as `read-write` for some containers and as `read-only` for others.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The following example changes the previous one.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] It mounts the directory as a read-only volume, by adding `ro` to the (empty by default) list of options, after the mount point within the container.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Where multiple options are present, you can separate them using commas.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The `--mount` and `-v` examples have the same result.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Use `docker inspect nginxtest` to verify that Docker created the read-only mount correctly.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Stop and remove the container, and remove the volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] When you mount a volume to a container, you can specify a subdirectory of the volume to use, with the `volume-subpath` parameter for the `--mount` flag.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The subdirectory that you specify must exist in the volume before you attempt to mount it into a container; if it doesn't exist, the mount fails.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Specifying `volume-subpath` is useful if you only want to share a specific portion of a volume with a container.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Say for example that you have multiple containers running and you want to store logs from each container in a shared volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] You can create a subdirectory for each container in the shared volume, and mount the subdirectory to the container.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The following example creates a `logs` volume and initiates the subdirectories `app1` and `app2` in the volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] It then starts two containers and mounts one of the subdirectories of the `logs` volume to each container.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] This example assumes that the processes in the containers write their logs to `/var/log/app1` and `/var/log/app2`.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] With this setup, the containers write their logs to separate subdirectories of the `logs` volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The containers can't access the other container's logs.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] When building fault-tolerant applications, you may need to configure multiple replicas of the same service to have access to the same files.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] There are several ways to achieve this when developing your applications.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] One is to add logic to your application to store files on a cloud object storage system like Amazon S3.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Another is to create volumes with a driver that supports writing files to an external storage system like NFS or Amazon S3.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Volume drivers let you abstract the underlying storage system from the application logic.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] For example, if your services use a volume with an NFS driver, you can update the services to use a different driver.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] For example, to store data in the cloud, without changing the application logic.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] When you create a volume using `docker volume create`, or when you start a container which uses a not-yet-created volume, you can specify a volume driver.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The following examples use the `rclone/docker-volume-rclone` volume driver, first when creating a standalone volume, and then when starting a container which creates a new volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The following example assumes that you have two nodes, the first of which is a Docker host and can connect to the second node using SSH.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] This example mounts the `/remote` directory on host `1.2.3.4` into a volume named `rclonevolume`.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Each volume driver may have zero or more configurable options, you specify each of them using an `-o` flag.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] This volume can now be mounted into containers.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The following example shows how you can create an NFS volume when creating a service.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] It uses `10.0.0.10` as the NFS server and `/var/docker-nfs` as the exported directory on the NFS server.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Note that the volume driver specified is `local`.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] You can mount a Samba share directly in Docker without configuring a mount point on your host.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The `addr` option is required if you specify a hostname instead of an IP.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] This lets Docker perform the hostname lookup.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] You can mount a block storage device, such as an external drive or a drive partition, to a container.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The following example shows how to create and use a file as a block storage device, and how to mount the block device as a container volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Under the hood, the `--mount` flag using the `local` storage driver invokes the Linux `mount` syscall and forwards the options you pass to it unaltered.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Docker doesn't implement any additional functionality on top of the native mount features supported by the Linux kernel.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] To explain this further, consider the following `mount` command example.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] This command mounts the `/dev/loop5` device to the path `/external-drive` on the system.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The following `docker run` command achieves a similar result, from the point of view of the container being run.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Running a container with this `--mount` option sets up the mount in the same way as if you had executed the `mount` command from the previous example.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] You can't run the `mount` command inside the container directly, because the container is unable to access the `/dev/loop5` device.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] That's why the `docker run` command uses the `--mount` option.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The following steps create an `ext4` filesystem and mounts it into a container.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The filesystem support of your system depends on the version of the Linux kernel you are using.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Create a loop device:`$ losetup -f --show disk.raw /dev/loop5` Note`losetup` creates an ephemeral loop device that's removed after system reboot, or manually removed with `losetup -d`.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Volumes are useful for backups, restores, and migrations.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] Use the `--volumes-from` flag to create a new container that mounts that volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] When the command completes and the container stops, it creates a backup of the `dbdata` volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] With the backup just created, you can restore it to the same container, or to another container that you created elsewhere.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] You can use these techniques to automate backup, migration, and restore testing using your preferred tools.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] A Docker data volume persists after you delete a container.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] To automatically remove anonymous volumes, use the `--rm` option.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] For example, this command creates an anonymous `/foo` volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] When you remove the container, the Docker Engine removes the `/foo` volume but not the `awesome` volume.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The `--rm` option works with both foreground and detached (`-d`) containers.
[src:docker-containers/storage-volumes] The anonymous volumes are cleaned up when the container exits.
